## References

- Shapiro, B. (2017).
Pathways to de-extinction: How close can we get to resurrection of an extinct species?
https://doi.org/10.1111/1365-2435.12705
This review discusses the major approaches to de-extinction, including selective breeding, somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT), and genetic engineering, while examining their scientific limitations and ecological implications.

- Novak, B. J. (2018).
De-Extinction.
https://doi.org/10.3390/genes9110548
This article provides an overview of de-extinction concepts, technologies, and conservation applications, including genome editing and genetic rescue strategies.

- Seddon, P. J., Moehrenschlager, A., & Ewen, J. G. (2016).
IUCN SSC Guiding Principles on Creating Proxies of Extinct Species for Conservation Benefit (Version 1.0).
International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).
https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/46248
This guideline discusses the potential role of creating proxies for extinct species as a conservation tool and highlights ecological and ethical considerations.

- National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI).
Genome Editing and CRISPR-Cas9 Technology.
https://www.genome.gov/about-genomics/policy-issues/Genome-Editing
This resource explains the principles of genome editing technologies and their applications in modern biotechnology.

- Colossal Biosciences.
De-Extinction Technology and Conservation Research.
https://colossal.com
Official information about ongoing research projects involving extinct species, genome engineering, and conservation biotechnology.-
